Thus monarchy with democracy. With democracy, status isn't assured, but is always the subject of agonistic conflict. With monarchy, status is fixed, ontological, absolute. I can't become king; nor do I want to be.

So the idea of a technological solution to the problem of contraception fails doubly: it fails to recognise the irreducible complexity both of the human body, and that of the wider social context.

Nature will always have its revenge.

The contraceptive pill is an example of this. So, it not only affects the micro-, but also the macro-level: hormonal shifts affects the lady's choice of partner; the guarantee of non-contraceptive sex has wider societal implication, of which we are all well aware.

The difficulty is that the various systems that make up a complex system simply can't be described in terms of quasi-Newtonian laws. Rather, the functioning of micro- and macro-systems interact in irreducibly complex ways, which scientific models approximate, but never capture.

Nor a coincidence of its popularity with liberals of all stripes. You can reduce the baffling complexity of the social world to a few simple rules: do what you want, as long as you don't hurt others, or variations to that effect.

The choices then are twofold: admit to the independent existence of reality; or, if it is to be a simulation, then acknowledge it must be the simulation of an omnipotent, omniscient mind.

I can do anything to anything, but never suffer a CE. There's never a situation when reality just doesn't know what perception to load next.

But that's simply impossible with any finite amount of computing power. No matter how finely-tuned your algorithm, *something* escapes it.

Further, the perceptions don't ever suffer from a combinatorial explosion. Perceptions are basically infinitely finely-grained, but also interact with each other at that level. The sights and sounds of my garden are always in perfect sync.

So the idea would be, just as a computer screen is the output of a program, all of our perceptions are the output of a mind. 

But, unlike a computer screen, these perceptions don't suffer "glitches". Go into a valley and you don't have to wait for the mind to load.

Further, TA is compatible with a God of limited intelligence, power &c., so can be superseded by scientific explanations. Evolution explains the careful design of organisms &c.

But Berkeley, by rejecting the concept of the material, can ask how perceptions are *ordered* per se.

So far, this is the Teleological Argument. But note that the Teleological Argument, at best, supports a form of Deism: God puts the structures in play, then steps back to watch the mechanism in work. For Berkeley, there's no stepping back: each perception is the work of God.

But if reality is mental, whose mind? Not ours: they are finite. Nor any pagan god: again, finite. Rather, it must be an infinite mind.

Why so? The thing about reality is that it's supremely *ordered*. Things happen in a regular fashion: too regular for a finite mind to produce.

There's a very good argument against the Simulation Hypothesis (idea that all of reality is a "Matrix"-style illusion from, of all people, Bishop Berkeley.

This is the real starting-point of philosophy: what must reality be like, such that it can be the object of discourse? What must the objects of thought be, so that they can actually exist in the real world?
Thus Idealism. Is reality mental? Well, what are we both talking about, when we talk about a pigeon? Different, mutually-inaccessible things. So we can't talk about the same thing. End of discussion.

If there is no self, or the self is simply a stream of thoughts, then there's no more reason to expect consistency between these thoughts than between the thoughts of two people. But dialogue is therefore impossible. Hence the belief cannot be defended.

In everyday life, they're useful for exposing the sincerity of the interlocutor: are you really committed to x, if x contradicts your stated belief y?

But they also have an ontological impact. What must *you*, the interlocutor, believe, if this conversation is even possible?

But the tripartite structure of art complicates this: if the artist is an intrinsic part of the status of the artwork, can't this help determine the work's meaning and merit?

Two examples: Borges' "Pierre Menard", where a 20th-c writer rewrites, work for work, the Quixote.

So it's an error to judge the work of art according to its ethics: the merit of an artwork is not *what* is being expressed, but *how*. The Triumph of the Will is an amazing film, even if its ethical principles are reprehensible.

Another: although a communicative act, the content of an artwork cannot be divested from said act. You cannot, e.g., summarise the "meaning" of the Aeneid in abstraction from the text as a whole (doubly so for e.g. music, dance, etc.)

A thought: intrinsic to a work of art is the implicit, but inherent relation between artist, work and audience. The work is only a work of art, because it is understood as an intentional communication: paint that falls randomly to make the Mona Lisa isn't an artwork.

...(Arma virumque cano, e.g., situating the work in the tradition of Homeric epic); or social (the rise of Augustus). Particularly in eras of literary sophistication, this sort of intertextual play is crucial to understanding the work.

So, Virgil's Aeneid is a supreme work of literature, because of its formal perfection in language and structure; it's on these, and these alone, that it gains its status.

But, OTOH, the same work of art *must* be understood in its context: whether artistic...

One question that's always bugged me about art is whether the artwork needs to be understood in its context (be that artistic, social, &c.)

On the one hand: no. A work of art is, so to speak, monadic: it is a world unto itself; its meaning, its merits, are internal.

But it makes the despair that Pinker et al. over the apparent "collapse" of rationality in contemporary society all the more delicious. Their "humanism" excludes the human from the get-go; their victory would be a victory for technocratic control.

Understood thus, "live in the pod, consume the product, eat the bugs" is nothing but the logical outcome of the Enlightenment. Atomised individuals, pursuing meaningless pleasures, but optimised for producing wealth and physical health.

No place for freedom or dignity in such a scheme; no place for flourishing, as something more than simple preference-satisfaction. The best measure that could be offered is health, wealth etc., divested of the goods to which they are means.

The account of man, to have any traction, ends up having to "objectify" him: to study him as if he were any other scientific object, subject to immutable natural laws. His actions are understood as subject to scientific understanding and technological control, no more.

The heirs of Protagoras (most notably Hume) make a clean break between fact and value: value is simple arbitrary preference, no part of the 'objective' world. But "mere preferences" can't make ethical demands on their own: if they're unsatisfied, so what?

The difficulty with Protagoras' principle is: what is the *man*, that is the measure of all things? 

The principle implies a denial of the objectivity of value: so what's valuable about man, that he may serve as a yardstick of all values? https://t.co/xUNpveWuH1

But it's instructive to study exactly what happens to the Sophistic movement. The urbane scepticism of Protagoras ends up in the immoralism of Thrasymachus or Callicles' Proto-Nietzschean strongman worship. A pattern that repeats: the liberal Nikolay vs the nihilist Bazarov.

A principle which functions both as an epistemic and an ethical principle (and is made all the more serious by living in a technological society, where all nature is a standing reserve to be exploited for man's use).

Reality itself having an inherently normative principle which the law must not only reflect, but take upon itself to promote. Law is a teacher, orienting us to the good.

The Sophists deny this tout court (excuse the pun): Protagoras' view that "man is the measure of all things".

The principle is expressed well in the (pseudo?)-Platonic dialogue Minos (a prequel to The Laws): "law intends to be a discovery of reality".

Law isn't simply convention, contract, or anything like that: rather, it is grounded in the nature of reality.

"Already in the fourth century B.C., Plato wrote these things in his last work the Laws and identified the cause of the Athenian political crisis precisely inthe breaking of the divine order – the cosmos – between these eternal principles and human laws": bullseye.
